sec.p:
Postpartum depression (PPD) is a public health problem worldwide(
1
). It is the most common psychiatric condition postpartum(
2
) and there is extensive material on the degree of disability that it is
likely to cause to the mother(
3
), its association with the delay in child development and behavior disorders
in adult life of the descendants(
4
).

In Chile, studies using standardized diagnostic criteria reported a prevalence of PPD of
about 20% in the primary health care (PHC) of public health system(
5
). In contrast, a study using the Edinburgh Postpartum Depression Scale
(EPDS), validated in Chile(
6
), indicated that 41.3% of mothers who are assisted in clinics are affected
by severe depressive symptoms between 2 and 3 months postpartum(
7
), that is, at risk of PPD.
